{
  "title": "What Do We Do with Culture?",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e25c1712bdaf31c0",
      "text": "Was fangen wir nur mit Kultur an?\nvon [[Peter Fuchs]] | Apr 5, 2016"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "060480c9a017fa99",
      "text": " Expressions like 'culture, cultures, interculturality, cultural event, corporate culture, etc.' are deeply fuzzy to me. If you ask people how they imagine what 'culture' means, they typically don't answer with a term, but with narratives, almost always with the implication that culture is something good and important. In the manner of Wittgenstein, one could ask people what culture is not, how one would notice that something does not belong to culture. Probably very similar replies could be heard: Unculture is not culture."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "dcefe184e7deeac5",
      "text": "According to this, hooligans, terrorist associations, angry citizens, fish-with-knives eaters ... would have no culture. It is something you can have or not. A bit of 'culture' sounds odd. If it is valid, then culture would be a system with a clear boundary: to be cultural or not to be cultural - tertium non datur."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "48da4d3a6161d1f4",
      "text": "Now it is the case that a one-to-one boundary cannot be determined, because one cannot know (apparently also empirically) which operation defines culture system(s). What should one call them? Cultivate, kulturen, kultirieren - I almost said: tirilieren?"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c395a4aaf816a508",
      "text": "If one cannot determine the phenomenon one is talking about, it is sometimes advisable to search for the function of the corresponding expression. When is it used, how and for what reasons? Which problems can be constructed as the solution of which the use of the symbol 'culture' could be understood?"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "97f4f2a5df0298af",
      "text": "The wild card that is usually consulted heuristically is the assumption that a phenomenon that cannot be grasped conceptually invisibilizes a problem, keeps it latent, caches it. In other words, this invisibilization would already be the function of culture. The difficulty is that one would not have uncovered the concealed with it, unless one would stoop to the zones of absolute self-reference: The function of culture would be to keep oneself behind the mountain for oneself, to make oneself 'away' for oneself - an ingenious solution, which, however, offers another problem: What can be reconstructed as the function of this self-extirpation?"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "149efc51e09caa92",
      "text": "It will be good to think drier in this situation:"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "9a2034f3a6193bb2",
      "text": "\"The topics are not created case by case, but on the other hand they are also not given in sufficient conciseness by the language, for example as vocabulary (because the language treats all words the same and does not yet dispose of the topic ability in communicative processes). Accordingly, there will be an intervening requirement mediating interaction and language - a kind of stock of possible topics available for rapid and quickly comprehensible assimilation in concrete communicative processes. We call this stockpile of topics [[culture]] and, when preserved specifically for communicative processes, [[semantics]]. Serious semantics worth preserving is thus a part of culture, namely that which is handed down to us by the history of concepts and ideas. Culture is not a necessarily normative content of meaning, but it is a determination of meaning ... which makes it possible to distinguish between fitting and non-fitting contributions ... in topic-related communication.\" (Luhmann 1984, p.224)"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b02b6f63a7404eb9",
      "text": "Thus, 'culture' is coolly determined. There is no longer any need for large-scale bramarbasing. It's about nothing but a 'stock of themes'. And why does this have to be camouflaged? [[Dirk Baecker]] formulates:"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "99647a307a77d3ac",
      "text": " Culture is realized by \" ... a very special type of observation [...], namely the observation of facts as distinctions and the observation of these distinctions for their form. Culture is [...] the third value that has become universal, the tertium datur as an objection against everything that society believes to put into the form of either/or. [...] Culture is necessarily aesthetic, if one understands by aesthetics, with Sören Kierkegaard, the establishment of an [[indifference]] between either and or.\" (Wozu Kultur? 2nd, expanded ed. Berlin 2001, p.105/106.)"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "80b18de14c3cffaa",
      "text": "It is this indifference that - to expand a little - plays a generalized role in modernity. The in-between of either/or is invisibilized. One can do something with it. It fits (simply because it's beautiful): "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "847c5d406a86ab23",
      "text": "Ulrich thinks: \"'It is a peculiarity of the European culture which cannot be overlooked that in it the 'world of the inside' is declared to be the most beautiful and deepest thing which life holds, but that this inner world is treated as a mere extension of the outer one. And it is just the balance secret of this culture, how this is done, if it is a public secret: One contrasts the outer world and the 'personality'; one assumes that the outer world arouses inner processes in a person which must enable him to respond appropriately; and by establishing in thought this trajectory which leads from a change in the world through the change of a person back to a change in the world, we gain that peculiar ambiguity which allows us to honor the world of the inner as the proper human sphere of sovereignty, and yet to presuppose of it that everything which goes on in it has in the end the task of flowing back into an orderly outward effect. '\" (Musil, R., Der Mann ohne Eigenschaften (ed. by Adolf Frisé), vol. II, Aus dem Nachlaß, Hamburg 1994, p.1200)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1593cf496ac3b956",
